Checking whether a given timetable satisfies all constraints can be done in polynomial time.

NP

A timetable can be verified quickly by checking conflicts.

NP-Complete

The decision problem:

"Can all exams be scheduled using k time slots?"

is NP-Complete because it is equivalent to the graph coloring problem.

NP-Hard

Finding the minimum number of time slots required is NP-Hard.

3. Graph Coloring Model
Each exam = vertex
Conflict between exams = edge
Time slot = color
Connected exams cannot have the same color (time slot).
5. Backtracking Algorithm

Steps:

Select an exam.
Assign a time slot.
Check conflicts.
If conflict occurs → backtrack.
Continue until all exams are scheduled.
Python Code: Exam Scheduling using Graph Coloring
# Exam Timetabling using Backtracking Graph Coloring

exams = ["E1", "E2", "E3", "E4"]

# Conflict graph
graph = {
    "E1": ["E2", "E3"],
    "E2": ["E1", "E3"],
    "E3": ["E1", "E2", "E4"],
    "E4": ["E3"]
}

# Available time slots
slots = 3

schedule = {}


# Check whether slot is valid
def is_valid(exam, slot):

    for neighbour in graph[exam]:

        if neighbour in schedule and schedule[neighbour] == slot:
            return False

    return True


# Backtracking function
def coloring(index):

    if index == len(exams):
        return True

    exam = exams[index]

    for slot in range(1, slots + 1):

        if is_valid(exam, slot):

            schedule[exam] = slot

            if coloring(index + 1):
                return True

            # Backtrack
            del schedule[exam]

    return False


# Execute
if coloring(0):

    print("Valid Exam Timetable:")

    for exam, slot in schedule.items():
        print(exam, "=> Time Slot", slot)

else:
    print("No possible timetable")
